\name{get.dawn.dusk.time}
\alias{get.dawn.dusk.time}
\title{Extract dawn and dusk times from a time series of par values}
\description{
Extracts the time that dawn and dusk (as.POSIXct) from a time series consisting of par (light intensity) values. Dawn is defined as the point where the par value goes from night -> day. Dusk is defined as the point where the par value goes from day -> to night. This is useful for gating purposes for flow- cytometry. Dawn and dusk tend to be the extremes of the flourences for most phytoplankton.
}
\usage{
get.dawndusk(x = data.frame(time, par), cutoff = 10)
}
\arguments{
\item{x}{
A data frame with two columns. The first column must be time values in as.POSIXct
format. The second column must be par values.
}
\item{cutoff}{
An integer representing the smallest par value that is considered 'daytime.' (We
recommend using 10).
}
}

\value{
A vector consisting of dawn and dusk time values in as.POSIXct format}
\author{
John MacMillan
}

\examples{
x <- data.frame(time = c(...),par = c(...))
x$time <- as.POSIXct(x$time)
dd.times <- get.dawn.dusk.time(x)
}
